Triple‑negative breast cancer (TNBC) lacks ER, PR, and HER2 expression, leaving limited targeted options. Genomic profiling frequently reveals PIK3CA mutations, PTEN loss, or AKT amplification, leading to constitutive PI3K activation. PI3K hydrolyses PIP2 to PIP3, recruiting AKT to the membrane where it is phosphorylated at T308 by PDK1 and S473 by mTORC2. Active AKT drives cell survival (via BAD, FOXO3a inhibition), proliferation (via S6K, 4E‑BP1 phosphorylation), and metabolic reprogramming. mTORC1 further amplifies protein synthesis and lipid biosynthesis, reinforcing oncogenesis.  

Inhibition of PI3K alone (e.g., buparlisib) results in compensatory mTORC1 reactivation;
